) (from RKC Eqs. 13 and 14). From Fig. 12, it is observed that with an increase of MoS2 partition number (or decrease of MoS2 crystal size), the catalyst activity would increase exponentially. Experimentally and at a laboratory scale, it is possible to synthesize tiny crystals of MoS2 up to quantum dots size. Hence, theoretically, the MoS2 quantum dots are expected to show excellent activity in HDS catalysis. Conversely, quantum dots production for the HDS process is out of the scope in the petroleum refining industries due to the production costs and limited technologies for large-scale production.

In the present experimental case, the activity comparison of high and lower pressure sulfided catalysts presented a large variation in HDS activity. The hnt-MoS2/Ni exhibited four-fold higher activity (105 × 10−8 mol.(gDBT.s)-1 than the mwnt-MoS2/Ni catalyst. The activity of the catalyst could be correlated to the MoS2 crystal size. The average slab length of MoS2 is 10.3 nm (stacking number = 6) for the mwnt-MoS2/Ni catalyst, which is approximately two times higher than the hnt-MoS2/Ni catalyst (length: 5.7 nm, stacking number: 4). These crystal diameter/average length (L) were determined from HRTEM measurements, where L is the longest dimension of the MoS2 hexagon, as shown in Figure S12. Since the regular MoS2 hexagon was considered for the derivation, the relation between crystal diameter (L) and side length (l) is L = 2l [65]. Applying this to the MoS2 crystal in mwnt-MoS2/Ni and hnt-MoS2/Ni were resulted in a side length of 5.15 and 2.85 nm, respectively. Therefore, when the MoS2 hexagon in the mwnt-MoS2/Ni (side length 5.15 nm) partitioned with a side length of 2.58 nm (= 5.15/2) produces 4 hexagons (i.e., ni
= 4). Then, according to RKC Eq. (13), the activity factor ( ai
) will be 4 (a2 = 4 → a = 2). Since the hexagon side length in the hnt-MoS2/Ni is 2.85 nm and is close to 2.58 nm in mwnt-MoS2/Ni. Therefore, the hnt-MoS2/Ni catalyst activity must be two times higher than the mwnt-MoS2/Ni. However, the experimental results showed 4 times higher activity (in terms of initial reaction rate, 105 × 10−8 molDBT.(gCat.s)-1) for the hnt-MoS2/Ni catalyst. This dispute between the theoretical and experimental results is due to presence of extended MoS2 hexagons in mwnt-MoS2/Ni catalyst. Furthermore, in the case of mwnt-MoS2/Ni catalyst, only the free MoS2 hexagons were considered for the average slab length, and other extended MoS2 slabs participated in the mw-nanotube formation were omitted. Therefore, the mwnt-MoS2/Ni catalyst exhibited low activity than expected which described in detail in the Supplementary Information (see Figure S13 and Table S3). As mentioned above, the side length of the MoS2 slab in the hnt-MoS2/Ni catalyst is 2.85 nm. Therefore, when four regular hexagons (hnt-MoS2/Ni) with a side length of 2.85 nm are combined, the resultant hexagon (also a regular shape) side length will be 5.7 nm, and the activity of the resultant crystal must be two times lower i.e., 52.5 × 10−8 molDBT.(gCat.s)-1. These results further confirm that mwnt-MoS2/Ni possesses extended MoS2 slabs (i.e., MoS2 slabs present in the multi-walled nanotubes) and lowers the HDS activity (24 × 10−8 molDBT.(gCat.s)-1). Hence, experimental results are correlated with the theoretically derived relation between the side length of the MoS2 crystal and HDS activity. Also, as described earlier, in-situ sulfidation is the commonly used technique in the petroleum refining industries. The hnt-MoS2/Ni catalyst could be produced easily by sulfiding the bulk NiMo-PMA catalyst. The current study shows a more facile method for synthesizing hierarchical nanotubes of MoS2 in large quantities and one of the best among the reported methods such as CVD [23–25] and grafting the MoS2 slabs on carbon nanotubes [5,8–10,28] etc.
